```cpp
int join_line() {
  static bool lineFirstTime = true; // Variable to keep track of the first time the line is encountered
  int state = 0; // Variable to hold the state of the line detection

  if (!lineFirstTime) { // Check if it's not the first time encountering the line
    state = 2; // Assume the robot is already on the line
  } else {
    digitalWrite(LED_PIN, true);
    // line found, turn on the spot to line up.
    while (abs(kinematics.Theta) < 40 * (3.14 / 180)) { // TURN ON THE SPOT TILL at 40 degrees, Allows our robot to get lined up enough for on line arc to take over.
      kinematics.update(); // need updated theta values.
      motors.setMotorPower(25, -20); // turn right for left sensor sees first
    }
    lineFirstTime = false; // Update the variable to indicate that the line has been encountered for the first time
    state = 1; // Set the state to 1 indicating that the line has been initially encountered
  }

  return state; // Return the state of the line detection
}
```

In this modified code, we introduce a new variable `lineFirstTime` to keep track of whether the robot has encountered the line before or not. The first time the line is detected, the code inside the `else` block will execute, aligning the robot with the line. After that, the variable `lineFirstTime` is updated to `false` to indicate that the line has been encountered for the first time. On subsequent invocations of this function, the code inside the `else` block will not execute, and the function will return the state value accordingly (2 indicating the robot is on the line).

